This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) category because it deals with generating images of geological facies models. It also involves the use of Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs), which is a popular technique in computer vision. 

The paper also involves machine learning techniques such as Information Maximizing Generative Adversarial Network (InfoGAN), Wasserstein distance, and Gradient Penalty (GP), which are commonly used in the sub-categories of Machine Learning (cs.LG), Graphics (cs.GR), Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE). 

Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV, followed by cs.LG, cs.GR, cs.AI, and cs.NE.
